 becoming more engaged in the resistance, they confronted critical issues in contemporary America: democratic decision making, environmental policy, legal rights, corporate responsibility, and the technology of nuclear waste.Some of the book's highlights include: conversations that took place between Governor Cuomo, Assemblyman Hasper, and the protestors, which thoughtfully probe who should bear the financial burden of a failed and dangerous technology; the scientific and technological issues discussed between Ted Taylor, a nuclear physicist who was one of the key people in the Manhattan project, and the leaders of the resistance; and the citizens' initiation of a lawsuit that eventually reached the Supreme Court and abrogated the central provision in the 1987 congressional law that mandated states build low-level nuclear dumps across the country. These dialogues and vignettes illustrate how the civil disobedience and dogged determination of the people of Allegany County changed the course of history.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Mrz 2024) 0aCivil disobediencezNew York (State)zAllegany County. 0aEnvironmental protectionzNew York (State)zAllegany CountyxCitizen participation. 0aLow level radioactive waste disposal facilitiesxLocationzNew York (State)zAllegany County. 0aLow level radioactive waste disposal facilitieszNew York (State)zAllegany CountyxPublic opinion. 0aNonviolencezNew York (State)zAllegany County. 0aPublic opinionzNew York (State)zAllegany County. 4aEnvironmental Studies : Environmental Studies. 4aNew York/Regional : New York/Regional. 4aPolitics and Law : Political Sociology. 4aSociology : Social Change. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Sociology / Rural.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUNY Press eBook Package  Backlist 2000-2013z978311148737340uhttps://www.degruyt